---
// FAQ.astro

const faqs = [
  {
    question: "How does Google Ads management for contractors actually work — and why can't I just run it myself?",
    schemaAnswer: "Google Ads for contractors puts your business in front of homeowners actively searching for your services. The auction system rewards relevance as much as budget — a well-structured campaign with strong negative keywords, high-quality landing pages, and proper bidding will outperform a higher-spending competitor. The STAB Framework (Spend, Targeting, Ads, Bidding) is the sequence used to optimize accounts. Running ads yourself means spending hours weekly reviewing search terms, adjusting bids, testing ad copy, and staying current with platform changes — unsustainable for a contractor running a business. Professional management produces campaigns that compound results over time.",
    htmlAnswer: `
      <p>
        <a href="/get-more-leads" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">Google Ads for contractors</a> is one of the most effective ways to put your business in front of homeowners who are actively searching for your services right now &mdash; not people who might need you someday, but people who are typing 'HVAC repair near me' or 'emergency plumber' into Google at this exact moment. That high commercial intent is why Google Ads consistently outperforms social media, mailers, and most other advertising channels for local service businesses.
      </p>
      <p>
        The way it works: you bid to appear at the top of Google's search results when someone in your service area searches relevant keywords. You only pay when someone actually clicks your ad. But the reality of running a profitable campaign is far more nuanced than that simple description suggests &mdash; and that's precisely why so many contractors lose money running their own ads.
      </p>
      <p>
        Google's auction system rewards relevance as much as it rewards budget. A contractor with a $2,000/month budget and a well-structured campaign &mdash; tightly themed ad groups, strong negative keyword lists, high-quality landing pages, and properly configured bidding strategies &mdash; will regularly outperform a competitor spending $8,000/month on a poorly managed account. The difference is Quality Score: Google's internal rating of how relevant your ads and landing pages are to what someone is searching for. A high Quality Score lowers your cost per click and improves your ad position simultaneously. It's the closest thing to a free money lever that exists in the Google Ads platform, and most self-managed accounts leave it almost entirely untouched.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="/get-more-leads" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">The STAB Framework</a> &mdash; Spend, Targeting, Ads, and Bidding &mdash; is the sequence we use to optimize every client account. The order matters. Most advertisers jump straight to adjusting bids when their cost per lead is too high. But bidding is the last lever you should touch, not the first. If your campaign structure is poor (Spend), your keyword targeting is bleeding into irrelevant searches (Targeting), or your ads and landing pages have a disconnect (Ads), no amount of bid manipulation will make the account profitable. You have to fix the foundation before you step on the accelerator.
      </p>
      <p>
        Running your own ads also means spending hours each week reviewing search term reports, identifying new negative keywords, testing ad copy variations, adjusting geographic bid modifiers, monitoring impression share, troubleshooting quality score drops, and staying current with Google's constant platform changes. For a contractor who's already managing crews, handling customer calls, and running a business &mdash; that time investment is genuinely unsustainable. The campaigns that generate real revenue for contractors are campaigns that are actively managed, not set-and-forgotten.
      </p>
      <p>
        What we provide is a system: structured campaigns, obsessive keyword hygiene, landing pages built to convert, and an ongoing optimization process that improves results over time rather than degrading. If your current ads aren't generating profitable leads, the problem is almost certainly somewhere in the structure &mdash; and it's fixable. <a href="/#contact" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">Let's look at your account.</a>
      </p>
    `
  },
  {
    question: "What is call tracking, and why does every contractor need it before spending another dollar on advertising?",
    schemaAnswer: "Call tracking assigns unique phone numbers to different marketing sources so every inbound call can be traced back to the exact source that generated it. Without it you're flying blind. You can see total call volume by source, which campaigns generate calls vs just clicks, your missed call rate (typically 15-30% for most contractors), call duration, and call recordings. The first 30 days of tracking data almost always changes how a contractor thinks about their marketing. Pairing call tracking with an AI answering service closes the loop completely.",
    htmlAnswer: `
      <p>
        <a href="/track-calls-leads" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">Call tracking</a> is the practice of assigning unique phone numbers to different marketing sources &mdash; your Google Ads campaigns, your Google Business Profile, your website, your Bing ads &mdash; so that every inbound call can be traced back to the exact source that generated it. Without it, you're flying completely blind. You know your phone rang. You have no idea why.
      </p>
      <p>
        Here's why that matters: most contractors are spending money on multiple marketing channels simultaneously &mdash; maybe Google Ads, a website, their Google Business Profile, and a directory listing or two. When the phone rings, you answer it. But without tracking, you have no way of knowing whether that call came from your $3,000/month Google Ads spend or from a free organic listing. You can't evaluate what's working, you can't cut what isn't, and you can't intelligently scale the channels that are actually delivering results. You're making financial decisions based on instinct rather than data.
      </p>
      <p>
        Call tracking solves this by giving you a complete picture of your lead flow. You see total call volume by source. You see which campaigns are generating calls and which are generating clicks but no calls &mdash; which is itself a critical signal. You see your missed call rate, which for most contractors is 15&ndash;30% of inbound calls during business hours before they've implemented any answering solution. You see call duration, which tells you whether conversations are converting into appointments or ending after 30 seconds. You can listen to recordings, which reveals whether your team's phone handling is helping or hurting conversion rates.
      </p>
      <p>
        The first 30 days of call tracking data almost always changes how a contractor thinks about their marketing. Channels they assumed were working turn out to be generating minimal calls. Sources they'd overlooked turn out to be driving significant volume. Missed calls they had no visibility into suddenly become visible as a quantifiable revenue leak. One roofing contractor we worked with discovered he was missing 23% of his inbound calls during business hours &mdash; nearly 1 in 4 calls going unanswered while his team was in the field. That's a calculation you can turn directly into dollars using your average job value and close rate.
      </p>
      <p>
        Pairing <a href="/track-calls-leads" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">call tracking</a> with our <a href="/answer-my-calls" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">AI answering service</a> closes the loop completely: you know exactly where every call came from, and you ensure that every call gets a professional, helpful response regardless of when it comes in or whether your team is available. That combination &mdash; visibility plus reliability &mdash; is the foundation of a lead generation system that actually compounds over time.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you're spending money on advertising without call tracking in place, you're essentially paying for marketing you can't measure. That's the most expensive way to run a business. <a href="/track-calls-leads" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">Get tracking in place</a> before you touch anything else.
      </p>
    `
  },
  {
    question: "How does an AI answering service work, and will my customers know they're talking to a machine?",
    schemaAnswer: "Modern AI answering systems use conversational AI to handle inbound calls your team can't answer. The AI answers in your company name, identifies the caller's need, collects key lead details (name, phone, address, problem description, urgency), and either transfers emergency calls live or logs the lead for follow-up. A structured summary is delivered to your team within minutes. Most callers complete the intake conversation without asking if it's AI. The alternative — voicemail — sees fewer than 20% of messages returned. AI answering ensures no call is lost.",
    htmlAnswer: `
      <p>
        Modern <a href="/answer-my-calls" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">AI answering systems for contractors</a> are built on conversational AI platforms &mdash; the same underlying technology that powers today's most sophisticated virtual assistants &mdash; and they bear almost no resemblance to the robotic, menu-driven phone trees of a decade ago. The voice is natural. The conversation flows. The AI asks follow-up questions based on what the caller says, handles interruptions gracefully, and adapts to the direction of the conversation rather than following a rigid script.
      </p>
      <p>
        Here's what actually happens when a call comes in that your team can't answer: the AI picks up in your company's name, greets the caller professionally, and begins a natural intake conversation. It identifies whether the caller is a new customer, an existing customer with a service issue, or something else entirely. For new customers, it collects the key information your team needs to respond: name, callback number, property address, the nature of the problem, how urgent it is, and any other details relevant to the type of work you do. For emergency situations &mdash; no heat in winter, burst pipe, AC failure in July &mdash; it can perform a live warm transfer, actually connecting the caller to an on-call technician rather than taking a message.
      </p>
      <p>
        Within minutes of the call ending, a structured lead summary is delivered to your team via text or email, and the full interaction is logged to your CRM automatically. No transcription errors, no partial messages, no 'they didn't leave their address' follow-up calls. The data is clean and consistent every time.
      </p>
      <p>
        Will callers know it's AI? Some will. Some won't. In our deployments, the majority of callers complete the intake conversation without asking. Among those who do ask, most are satisfied once the AI explains it's a virtual assistant helping gather their information so the right person can call them back. The small percentage who have a strong preference for a human can be routed to voicemail or a live line depending on your configuration. What matters most to homeowners with an urgent service need isn't whether they're talking to a human or an AI &mdash; it's whether they're being heard, whether their information is being captured correctly, and whether they're confident someone will actually call them back. A well-built AI answering system delivers all three.
      </p>
      <p>
        The alternative &mdash; voicemail &mdash; is dramatically worse by every measurable metric. Fewer than 20% of voicemails left for businesses are ever returned. When callers hit voicemail on an urgent service call, most of them hang up and call the next contractor on Google. The AI doesn't just answer the call; it ensures the opportunity doesn't disappear.
      </p>
      <p>
        For contractors who are concerned about the technology handling complex or sensitive situations, the system is fully configurable. We can set thresholds for when the AI escalates immediately to a live person, what information it collects, and how it handles specific caller scenarios. It's a tool that fits around your business &mdash; not the other way around. <a href="/answer-my-calls" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">See how it works in practice.</a>
      </p>
    `
  },
  {
    question: "What separates a contractor website that generates leads from one that just exists on the internet?",
    schemaAnswer: "The difference is architecture — structural decisions about information hierarchy, page structure, internal linking, technical foundations, and conversion pathways. A converting site loads fast on mobile (under 3 seconds), answers three questions immediately: do you do this work, do you serve my area, how do I call you. It has dedicated pages for each core service (not one 'Services' page), location-specific pages for each city served, trust signals (reviews, photos, credentials) on every page near the call to action, and a clickable phone number everywhere.",
    htmlAnswer: `
      <p>
        The difference between a <a href="/contractor-website" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">contractor website that generates consistent leads</a> and one that sits quietly collecting digital dust is almost never about aesthetics. It's about architecture &mdash; the underlying structural decisions that determine whether a visitor can find what they need, trust what they see, and take action before they click away to a competitor.
      </p>
      <p>
        The first thing a high-performing contractor website gets right is speed. More than 60% of local service searches happen on mobile devices. A site that takes more than three seconds to load loses roughly half its visitors before they ever see your content &mdash; and those visitors don't wait or try again. They go to the next result. This means every design decision has to be evaluated through a mobile performance lens: compressed images, clean lightweight code, reliable hosting, and nothing that slows the critical render path.
      </p>
      <p>
        The second thing is information hierarchy. A homeowner landing on your site at 11 PM with a leaking roof isn't there to read your company story or browse your gallery. They need to know three things within ten seconds: Do you do the work I need? Do you serve my area? How do I reach you right now? A converting website answers all three immediately &mdash; above the fold, on every page, with a phone number that's clickable and a primary call to action that's unmissable. Most contractor websites make visitors hunt for this information. The best ones make it impossible to miss.
      </p>
      <p>
        The third is service page structure. One of the most common and costly mistakes contractors make is having a single 'Services' page that tries to rank for every keyword simultaneously. That page ranks for almost none of them. What works is dedicated pages for each core service &mdash; each written for a specific customer searching for a specific thing, each with its own headline, trust signals, social proof, and call to action. If you serve five cities, you need location-specific pages for each city. 'Plumbing Repair in [City A]' and 'Plumbing Repair in [City B]' are separate pages, each targeted to local search.
      </p>
      <p>
        Trust architecture matters just as much as structure. Reviews belong on every service page near the call to action &mdash; not isolated on a testimonials page nobody visits. Real photos of your work and your team convert better than stock photography. Specific claims ('We've installed over 800 HVAC systems in [City] since 2009') build more trust than general ones ('We provide quality service'). Your license number, insurance status, and any guarantees you offer should be visible without scrolling.
      </p>
      <p>
        Finally, the technical foundation has to be solid: clean URL structure, proper heading hierarchy, local business schema markup, a submitted sitemap, and canonical tags to prevent duplicate content issues across location pages. None of this is glamorous. All of it determines whether Google can understand your site well enough to rank it for the searches that matter.
      </p>
      <p>
        We build <a href="/contractor-website" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">contractor websites</a> from the structure up, with lead generation as the primary goal. If your current site isn't generating the calls it should, the problem is almost certainly in the foundation &mdash; and it's fixable. <a href="/#contact" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">Let's look at what's holding it back.</a>
      </p>
    `
  },
  {
    question: "How does Google Maps optimization work, and why do some contractors dominate the three-pack while others are invisible?",
    schemaAnswer: "Google uses three factors for local rankings: relevance (how well your Google Business Profile matches the search), distance (proximity to the searcher), and prominence (how well-known and trusted your business is online). Prominence is driven by review quantity, review rating, review recency, review response rate, website authority, and NAP consistency across all directories. Contractors with 80+ reviews consistently outperform those with 20 reviews even if closer to the searcher. Building a system that consistently generates reviews is the single highest-leverage thing most contractors can do for Maps visibility.",
    htmlAnswer: `
      <p>
        The Google Maps three-pack &mdash; the three local business listings that appear at the top of search results for queries like 'HVAC company near me' or 'plumber in [city]' &mdash; is one of the most valuable pieces of digital real estate that exists for local service contractors. When you rank there, you're visible to every homeowner in your area who is actively searching for your services, before they've even scrolled to the organic results or paid ads. Ranking in the three-pack is often more valuable than a page-one organic ranking because it appears above it.
      </p>
      <p>
        Google uses three primary factors to determine who appears in the three-pack: relevance, distance, and prominence. Understanding what each means in practice is where most contractors get tripped up, because the factors that drive local rankings are different from the factors that drive regular organic rankings.
      </p>
      <p>
        Relevance is about how well your <a href="/google-maps" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">Google Business Profile</a> matches what the searcher is looking for. Your primary category should be as specific as possible. Your services list should include every type of work you do. Your business description should be written clearly using the actual service terms your customers search for. Reviews that mention specific services &mdash; 'they fixed my AC,' 'great fence installation' &mdash; signal to Google exactly what you're capable of.
      </p>
      <p>
        Distance is straightforward: Google uses the searcher's location to determine proximity. The closer a business is to the searcher, the better it ranks, all else being equal. This is why a single profile can't rank equally well across a 40-mile service area. The further you get from your registered address, the harder it is to appear. For contractors who serve multiple cities, this creates a real strategic challenge that requires city-specific content, consistent review generation across the full service area, and proper service area configuration in the profile.
      </p>
      <p>
        Prominence is the most complex factor &mdash; and the one most contractors underinvest in. Google uses prominence to measure how well-known and trusted your business is, both online and offline. The key signals are review quantity, review rating, review recency, review response rate, website authority, and the consistency of your NAP (Name, Address, Phone) data across every place it appears online. A business with 80 reviews has a structural advantage over a business with 20 reviews, even if the 20-review business is closer to the searcher and has a higher average rating. Volume matters.
      </p>
      <p>
        The practical implication: the contractors who dominate the three-pack in competitive markets aren't necessarily the best contractors &mdash; they're the ones who have built systems around getting reviews consistently and managing their profile actively. A review generation system that automatically asks every completed-job customer for a Google review, while the experience is still fresh, is the single highest-leverage thing most contractors can do for their Maps visibility right now. Combined with our <a href="/5-star-reviews" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">5-star review generation service</a>, the results compound over time.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you're not ranking in the three-pack for your primary services in your primary market, the gap is almost always in one or more of these areas: an incomplete or poorly optimized profile, insufficient review volume, inconsistent NAP data across directories, or a website that's too weak to support your local authority signals. All of these are fixable. <a href="/google-maps" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">See how we approach Google Maps optimization</a> for contractors.
      </p>
    `
  },
  {
    question: "What is an AI chatbot for contractors, and how is it different from the AI answering service?",
    schemaAnswer: "The AI answering service handles inbound phone calls. The AI chatbot handles inbound website visitors who have questions but aren't ready to call. Without a chatbot, visitors who don't find their answer leave silently — no missed call notification, no record. The chatbot engages visitors, answers common questions about services, service area, pricing, and availability, and captures lead information from people who would never fill out a contact form. This is especially valuable for after-hours traffic — evenings and weekends when homeowners browse but offices are closed.",
    htmlAnswer: `
      <p>
        The <a href="/answer-my-calls" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">AI answering service</a> handles inbound phone calls &mdash; the customers who pick up their phone and dial your number. The <a href="/ai-chatbot" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">AI chatbot</a> handles inbound website visitors &mdash; the customers who land on your website and have questions but aren't ready to call. They're complementary tools that cover different points in the customer journey, and together they create something most contractor businesses don't have: full coverage across every inbound channel, at every hour of the day.
      </p>
      <p>
        The reality of contractor website traffic is that a significant portion of visitors won't call. Some aren't ready. Some prefer typing to talking. Some have a quick question they want answered before committing to a phone conversation. Without a chatbot, those visitors read what they can find, don't get their question answered, and leave. The lead is lost silently &mdash; no missed call notification, no voicemail, no record of the visit. It simply disappears.
      </p>
      <p>
        An AI chatbot changes that dynamic. When a visitor lands on your website, the chatbot is available to engage immediately &mdash; answering questions about your services, your service area, your pricing range, your availability, and your process. It can handle the most common pre-sale questions without any involvement from your team: 'Do you work in [city]?' 'Do you offer financing?' 'What's your response time for emergency calls?' 'Are you licensed and insured?' These questions get answered instantly, around the clock, without tying up your phone lines or requiring your office staff to be available.
      </p>
      <p>
        More importantly, the chatbot captures lead information from visitors who would never fill out a contact form. When someone is engaged in a conversation and asks about availability, the chatbot can naturally transition to collecting their name, phone number, and service need &mdash; turning a passive visitor into an active lead without the friction of a formal form submission. Those leads are delivered to your team with full conversation context, so whoever follows up already knows what the customer needs.
      </p>
      <p>
        For after-hours traffic &mdash; evenings and weekends, which are peak browsing times for homeowners researching service contractors &mdash; a chatbot is particularly valuable. A homeowner whose HVAC system stopped working at 9 PM on a Saturday isn't going to wait until Monday morning to start looking for help. They're on Google and on websites right now. If your website has a chatbot that can engage them, answer their questions, and capture their information, you have a lead in your queue by the time your team arrives Monday morning. Without it, that homeowner has already hired someone else.
      </p>
      <p>
        The pairing of <a href="/answer-my-calls" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">AI phone answering</a> and <a href="/ai-chatbot" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">AI website chat</a> means that no matter how a potential customer tries to reach you &mdash; phone or web, business hours or midnight &mdash; they get a professional, helpful response that captures their information and keeps the lead moving forward. That's the complete inbound coverage most contractors don't have. <a href="/#contact" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">Let's set it up for your business.</a>
      </p>
    `
  },
  {
    question: "How do I get more 5-star Google reviews, and why does review volume matter so much for contractors?",
    schemaAnswer: "Review volume is often the deciding factor between ranking in the Google Maps three-pack and being invisible. A business with 90 reviews at 4.7 stars converts more than a business with 12 reviews at 5.0 stars — volume signals legitimacy. The system that works: a script for technicians to ask at job close, an automated text follow-up sent within the hour with a direct review link, and responses to every review within 48 hours. The best time to ask is immediately after the job when satisfaction is highest. Direct text links that open the review form in one tap remove friction and dramatically increase completion rates.",
    htmlAnswer: `
      <p>
        <a href="/5-star-reviews" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">Google reviews</a> are the most underused growth lever most contractors have available to them right now &mdash; and the gap between the contractors who systematically generate them and those who don't is often the entire difference between ranking in the Maps three-pack and being invisible to local searchers. It's not a minor factor. In competitive markets, review volume and recency are often the deciding variable between businesses that are otherwise similar in quality and proximity.
      </p>
      <p>
        Here's why review volume matters so much beyond just the ranking signal: when a homeowner is choosing between three contractors in the Maps pack, they're reading the reviews. A business with 90 reviews and a 4.7-star rating will convert more clicks than a business with 12 reviews and a 5.0-star rating, even though the second business has a higher average. The 90-review business feels established. It feels validated by a community of real customers. The 12-review business feels like it might have just gotten lucky with a few satisfied customers. Volume signals legitimacy in a way that a perfect score does not.
      </p>
      <p>
        The contractors who consistently dominate their local Maps results share one characteristic: they treat review generation as a standard operating procedure, not an occasional ask. That means a specific system &mdash; a script for technicians to deliver at job close, an automated text follow-up sent within the hour with a direct review link, and a protocol for responding to every review within 48 hours. That system runs consistently regardless of how busy the team is, and the results compound over time in ways that no other single marketing activity can match.
      </p>
      <p>
        The timing of the ask matters more than most contractors realize. The best moment to request a review is when the customer expresses satisfaction &mdash; right when the job is done, before the technician leaves, while the experience is still fresh and the emotional high of a solved problem is still present. That window closes quickly. A customer who says 'great job' on Tuesday and gets a review request email the following Monday has moved on. The urgency is gone. The response rate drops dramatically.
      </p>
      <p>
        Reducing friction in the review process is equally important. Most customers who are willing to leave a review abandon the process because it requires too many steps. A direct link that opens the Google review form in one tap removes that friction almost entirely. The text should be short, personal-sounding, and come from the technician's name or the owner's name &mdash; not a generic company account. 'Hi [Name], it was great working at your place today. If you have a minute, here's a direct link to leave us a Google review &mdash; it means a lot to us: [link].' That format outperforms generic email blasts by a wide margin.
      </p>
      <p>
        Responding to every review &mdash; positive and negative &mdash; also matters. It signals to Google that your business is active. It shows future customers how you handle feedback. A calm, professional response to a negative review often does more for conversion than a dozen additional five-star reviews, because it demonstrates the character of the business. Never argue in a public response. Acknowledge, offer to make it right, and move the conversation offline.
      </p>
      <p>
        Our <a href="/5-star-reviews" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">review generation system</a> automates the consistent parts &mdash; the timing, the follow-up, the tracking &mdash; while keeping the messages feeling personal. Combined with our <a href="/google-maps" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">Google Maps optimization</a>, it's the fastest legitimate path to improving your local search visibility. <a href="/#contact" class="text-primary hover:text-accent hover:opacity-80 underline decoration-primary/50 underline-offset-4 transition-colors font-medium">Let's build that system for your business.</a>
      </p>
    `
  }
];

const schemaData = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": faqs.map(faq => ({
    "@type": "Question",
    "name": faq.question,
    "acceptedAnswer": {
      "@type": "Answer",
      "text": faq.schemaAnswer
    }
  }))
};
const schemaText = JSON.stringify(schemaData);
---

<section id="faq" class="py-24 bg-background overflow-hidden relative border-t border-border">
  <!-- Schema -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={schemaText} />
  
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="text-center mb-16">
      <h3 class="text-primary font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-sm mb-3">Got Questions?</h3>
      <h2 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-foreground mb-6 tracking-tight">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <p class="text-lg text-slate-600 leading-relaxed max-w-2xl mx-auto">Everything contractors ask us before getting started &mdash; answered in full detail, without the marketing fluff.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-4" id="faq-accordion">
      {faqs.map((faq, index) => (
        <div class="faq-item rounded-xl border border-border bg-white/5 overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300 hover:border-primary/20 data-[open=true]:border-primary/40 data-[open=true]:shadow-lg data-[open=true]:shadow-primary/5 group" data-open="false">
          <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between p-6 text-left focus:outline-none" aria-expanded="false">
            <span class="font-bold text-foreground text-lg group-data-[open=true]:text-primary transition-colors pr-8">{faq.question}</span>
            <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 rounded-full border border-slate-300 flex items-center justify-center text-foreground group-data-[open=true]:text-primary group-data-[open=true]:border-primary/50 transition-colors">
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="faq-icon-plus block group-data-[open=true]:hidden"><path d="M5 12h14"/><path d="M12 5v14"/></svg>
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="faq-icon-minus hidden group-data-[open=true]:block"><path d="M5 12h14"/></svg>
            </span>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-content hidden text-slate-700 px-6 pb-6 pt-2 border-t border-border text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-4">
             <Fragment set:html={faq.htmlAnswer} />
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <!-- Bottom CTA Box -->
    <div class="mt-16 bg-white border border-border rounded-2xl p-8 md:p-10 text-center flex flex-col items-center justify-center max-w-2xl mx-auto shadow-2xl shadow-white/5 relative overflow-hidden">
        <!-- subtle glow -->
        <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-br from-amber-500/10 to-transparent pointer-events-none"></div>
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-black text-[#020617] mb-3 relative z-10">Still have questions?</h3>
        <p class="text-[#020617]/70 font-medium mb-8 relative z-10 text-sm md:text-base max-w-lg">Every contractor's situation is different. Let's talk through yours &mdash; no pitch, just a straight conversation about what's working and what isn't.</p>
        <a href="/#contact" class="inline-flex items-center justify-center px-8 py-4 bg-primary hover:bg-amber-600 text-white font-black rounded-lg transition-transform hover:scale-95 shadow-xl shadow-primary/20 relative z-10">
          Get a Free Consultation
        </a>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>

<script>
  const faqItems = document.querySelectorAll('.faq-item');
  
  faqItems.forEach(item => {
    const btn = item.querySelector('.faq-toggle');
    const content = item.querySelector('.faq-content');
    
    if (btn && content) {
      btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const isOpen = item.getAttribute('data-open') === 'true';
        
        // Close all others
        faqItems.forEach(otherItem => {
           if (otherItem !== item) {
             otherItem.setAttribute('data-open', 'false');
             const otherBtn = otherItem.querySelector('.faq-toggle');
             const otherContent = otherItem.querySelector('.faq-content');
             if(otherBtn) otherBtn.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'false');
             if(otherContent) otherContent.classList.add('hidden');
           }
        });
        
        // Toggle current
        if (isOpen) {
          item.setAttribute('data-open', 'false');
          btn.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'false');
          content.classList.add('hidden');
        } else {
          item.setAttribute('data-open', 'true');
          btn.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'true');
          content.classList.remove('hidden');
        }
      });
    }
  });
</script>
